You already know at the implementation, that's why it seems the same.
The test would also pass for a simple re-cast roundtrip:
```C++
auto ArithToUint256_mock(const arith_uint256 &a) { return *reinterpret_cast<const uint256*>(&a); }
auto UintToArith256_mock(const uint256 &a) { return *reinterpret_cast<const arith_uint256*>(&a); }
BOOST_AUTO_TEST_CASE(conversion)
{
    for (const arith_uint256& arith : {ZeroL, OneL, R1L, R2L}) {
        const auto u256{uint256::FromHex(arith.GetHex()).value()};
        BOOST_CHECK_EQUAL(UintToArith256_mock(ArithToUint256_mock(arith)), arith);
        BOOST_CHECK_EQUAL(UintToArith256_mock(u256), arith);
        BOOST_CHECK_EQUAL(u256, ArithToUint256_mock(arith));
        BOOST_CHECK_EQUAL(ArithToUint256_mock(arith).GetHex(), UintToArith256_mock(u256).GetHex());
    }

    for (const uint8_t num : {0, 1, 0xff}) {
        BOOST_CHECK_EQUAL(UintToArith256_mock(uint256{num}), arith_uint256{num});
        BOOST_CHECK_EQUAL(uint256{num}, ArithToUint256_mock(arith_uint256{num}));
    }
}
```

That's why I though we should cover it with hard-coded examples which cannot cheat by passing the parameter around.
(note, the previous hard-coded ones also pass for the above `_mock` methods, we should find better ones to obviate why the mocks are incorrect)

